BLOOD ON THE PINE
THE SCRUNGLY STRANGER
The Bannered Mare was warm with celebration and relief. The Battleborn case was closed, the gold was counted, and for a moment, the party could simply enjoy being alive and successful.
The door to the Bannered Mare opened and Orion stepped through, scanning the room until he spotted them. The Breton warrior grinned and made his way to their table. There were greetings and clasped forearmsΓÇöit had been some time since they'd adventured together. He pulled up a chair and settled in just as an old Khajiit woman approached their table. She was small, hunched, her fur matted and her robes patched more times than anyone could count. She moved with the careful steps of someone long accustomed to the world's indifference.
"This one smells soup," she said, her voice rough but not unfriendly. "Good soup. Ja'ha has coin, but..." She held up a few worn septims.
Kyboah looked at the others, then gestured to an empty chair. "Sit. Eat."
Ja'ha settled into the seat with visible satisfaction and ate with the focused intensity of someone who didn't know when the next meal might come. When the party mentioned their upcoming journey to Falkreath, she looked up from her bowl.
"Ja'ha knows the road south," she said. "Has walked it many times."
The implication was clear. The party exchanged glances and shrugged. They'd traveled with stranger companions.
Davinia, however, had other plans. "Danica needs another day or two to settle her affairs with the temple," she explained. "I'll wait for her, then we'll catch up with you in Falkreath."
Falsetto announced her own intentions with a theatrical gesture. "Whiterun suits me. The Bannered Mare appreciates fine entertainment." She bowed. "Should you need me, you know where to find me."
THE CART DEBATE
The next morning, they stood in the marketplace facing a practical problem. Bjorn had already departed for Solitude to meet the High King, and they needed transportation.
"I could just run us there," Kyboah said.
Saijah gave him a long look. "You want to carry all of us and our gear across half of Skyrim."
"I'm fast."
"You're not a horse."
Alfonso examined the public cart. "The cart has wheels and a driver. I assume we all value having functioning spines."
Orion walked around the cart, checking its construction. "Looks sturdy enough," he said with a nod.
Ja'ha, who had appeared beside them with her meager belongings, added: "This one has ridden on backs of foolish Khajiit. Cart is better."
They hired the cart.
FALKREATH
The journey south was uneventful until they reached the forests of Falkreath Hold. The pines grew thick and tall, their branches creating a canopy that turned afternoon into twilight. Fog clung to everything, never quite lifting.
When they finally arrived in Falkreath, something felt immediately wrong. The streets were empty. Not quietΓÇöempty. Just silence and the creak of wood settling.
The air itself felt oppressive, heavy with more than just fog.
They made their way to the Dead Man's Drink. Alfonso, however, broke off from the group without explanation.
"I'm going to look around," he said, and headed toward what looked like a graveyard in the distance.
Inside the tavern, the atmosphere was thick with tension. Perhaps a dozen people sat scattered throughout the common room, all hunched over their drinks, speaking in whispers if they spoke at all.
The innkeeper, a Nord woman with worry lines carved deep into her face, looked up as they entered. Her smile was forced.
"Welcome to Dead Man's Drink," she said. "Can I get you something?"
"We're new in town," Kyboah said. "What's going on here? Why does everything feel so..."
"Wrong?" The innkeeper's smile vanished. "You'd have to ask the Jarl's steward about that. Nenya. She'sΓÇö"
"Right here," a voice said from behind them.
They turned to find a Dark Elf woman standing there, her deep reddish-black hair framing a face that clearly hadn't seen proper sleep in days. She'd been sitting in the corner, watching them.
"You're the ones Maven Black-Briar hired for that business in Riften, aren't you?" Nenya asked.
The party exchanged bewildered looks.
"Riften?" Kyboah repeated, his brow furrowing.
"The job Maven hired you for," Nenya said, impatience creeping into her voice. "Thornheart Grove? The missing woodcutters?"
They looked at each other blankly. Between the battle with the Heart-Keeper, the journey to Whiterun, the entire Battleborn investigation, and everything that had happened since, the Riften job felt like it had been months ago instead of weeks.
"No," Saijah said uncertainly.
Nenya's expression tightened with frustration.
Then Saijah's face brightened with recognition. "Oh wait! That maze thing! With the corrupted tree!"
"And the wolves made of thorns," Kyboah added, memory returning.
Alfonso nodded slowly. "The priestess we rescued."
The party laughedΓÇöthe slightly awkward laughter of people who'd been through so much recently that jobs and employers had started blurring together in their minds.
Nenya did not laugh. She looked at them like she was reassessing whether they'd hired competent professionals or just lucky idiots.
"Right. Okay. Whatever." She pulled out a chair and sat down heavily. "Maven said you were professionals, and we need professionals."
THE GRAVEYARD
Alfonso found the graveyard easily enough. It was massiveΓÇötombstones stretching up the hillsides in every direction, outnumbering the living population by what had to be a hundred to one.
He walked among the graves until he found a relatively fresh one. With a gesture, spectral hands materialized and began to dig. It didn't take long to reach the coffin.
The body inside was an elderly Nord, perhaps a week dead. Alfonso examined it clinically, then tore off the corpse's hand. He tried a few bites. The flesh was cold and unpleasant, too difficult to process, minimal return.
He tossed the hand aside and climbed out of the grave, giving up on the endeavor.
What he didn't know was that Ja'ha had followed him from the tavern, moving with the quiet stealth of a cat on the hunt. She'd watched the entire process from behind a nearby tombstone with complete neutrality.
As Alfonso walked away, she stepped out, picked up the discarded hand, sniffed it once, and tucked it into her robes. Then she followed him back toward the Dead Man's Drink.
FOUR DISAPPEARANCES
By the time Alfonso and Ja'ha returned to the tavern, Nenya had laid out the situation.
"Four people," she said. "Gone. Vanished from locked rooms in the middle of the night. No signs of struggle. No forced entry. Nothing."
She counted them off on her fingers. "KustΓÇöblacksmith's apprentice. HertΓÇölumberjack from the mill. And an elderly Wood Elf couple from Cyrodiil, merchants who'd come here to conduct some final business before retiring."
"Theories?" Alfonso asked, sliding into a seat.
"None that hold up. The town guard thinks bandits, but locked rooms don't support that. The locals are whispering about ghosts and curses." Nenya's expression made it clear what she thought of both theories. "I need investigators, not soldiers who see what they expect to see, and not townsfolk inventing ghost stories."
She slid a piece of parchment across the tableΓÇöa writ of authority from the Jarl. "Eight hundred gold per person when this is resolved. The woodcutterΓÇöHertΓÇölived in a shack near the mill. That's where I'd start."
THE WOODCUTTER'S SHACK
The shack stood in a small clearing near the mill, exactly as Nenya had described. The door was closed but not locked. No signs of forced entry. No signs of struggle.
Inside, everything was neat and orderly. Too orderlyΓÇölike someone had tidied up before leaving, except they hadn't left willingly.
Saijah found a journal on a small table. She flipped through the recent entries and paused on one page.
"Listen to this," she said. "He's talking about his niece's birthday. Says he's excited to finish the gift he's been working on." She gestured to wood shavings scattered near a workbench. "He was whittling something."
They searched the rest of the shack but found nothing else of note. Whoever or whatever had taken Hert had done so without leaving any conventional evidence.
THE MILL
The Half-Moon Mill stood beside a rushing stream, its great wheel turning but the building itself silent. No rhythmic thud of the saw. No voices calling out. Just the creak of wood and the splash of water.
Inside the attached house, they found Hern sitting at a table, methodically working on a small wooden carving. As they approached, they could see it was a duckΓÇöhalf-finished, the details carefully rendered.
"For his niece," Kyboah said quietly.
Hern looked up, his eyes red-rimmed. "You're here about Hert." It wasn't a question.
"We are," Saijah said, sitting down across from him. "Can you tell us what happened?"
"Nothing happened. That's the thing." Hern's hands stilled on the carving. "She was there when we went to sleep. Gone when I woke up. Door was still latched from the inside. No struggle, no sound, nothing."
He set down his carving tools. "She'd just taken a big job. Lord Valerius wanted choice pine lumber delivered to the Hall of the Honored Dead. The pay would have..." He gestured vaguely at the mill, at his life. "It would have fixed everything. Let us hire help. Give ElinaΓÇöour daughterΓÇöa better future."
Hern stood and moved to a ledger on a shelf. "The order's still here. Half-processed. I can't finish it alone, and without that payment, the mill is finished anyway."
He showed them the orderΓÇöa massive amount of lumber, all destined for the Hall of the Honored Dead, all commissioned by someone named Lord Valerius.
"It'll never be done in time," Hern said, his voice breaking. "And I can'tΓÇöI can't even think about work when she's out there somewhere, orΓÇö"
Saijah touched his shoulder gently. The wood cutter accepted the comfort, his grief palpable and raw.
The party exchanged glances. Then, without any formal discussion, they made a decision.
"We'll finish it," Kyboah said.
Hern looked up, startled. "What?"
"The order. We'll help you complete it."
"But you're investigators, you don't have time toΓÇö"
"We'll make time," Saijah said firmly.
A DAY'S WORK
They spent the entire next day at the mill.
Kyboah's strength proved invaluable for hauling logs and operating the heavy saw. Orion worked the lumber stacks, his warrior's build suited to the heavy lifting. Alfonso, despite his usual detachment from physical labor, handled measuring and marking with methodical precision. Saijah moved between tasks with practiced efficiency. Even Ja'ha contributed, demonstrating surprising competence with hand tools while offering running commentary.
Hern worked alongside them, his hands finding their familiar rhythm. By evening, the order was completeΓÇöstacks of perfectly processed choice pine, ready for delivery.
"Thank you," Hern said, and there were tears in his eyes. "I don't know how to repay this."
"Just tell us where to deliver it," Kyboah said, brushing sawdust from his fur.
"The Hall of the Honored Dead. In the graveyard." Hern's expression darkened. "Be careful there. That place... something's not right about it."
THE HALL OF THE HONORED DEAD
They loaded the lumber onto a cart and hauled it through the massive graveyard as evening approached. The Hall of the Honored Dead stood at the heart of the cemeteryΓÇöa weathered stone structure that seemed older than the town itself.
The door was sealed. Not just closed, but seamlessly sealed, with a faint hum of magical energy emanating from it.
Alfonso examined it with professional interest. "It's warded. Sophisticated work. The seal is keyed to a specific phraseΓÇömost likely the caster's name."
"So we need to know who cast it," Saijah said.
"Correct."
They searched the area and found something strange: a single Nightshade blossom sitting on the threshold, dark petals perfectly arranged. Tucked between the petals was a small piece of parchment.
Kyboah unfolded it and read aloud:
"My collection nears completion. The preservation ritual will be finished under the new moon's gaze. It is a pity you will not be here to witness the culmination of my work. The vintage must be sealed before it spoils."
The party looked at each other.
"A taunt," Alfonso said.
"Or a warning," Saijah added. "The new moon is tomorrow night."
"Doesn't help us with the name," Kyboah said, staring at the sealed door.
They'd hit an impasse. The lumber sat on the cart, unable to be delivered. The door remained sealed. And somewhere inside, four people were being held for some kind of "preservation ritual."
"We need more information," Alfonso said. "The blacksmith's apprentice was one of the victims. Maybe his master knows something."
LOD'S FORGE
They found Lod at the forgeΓÇöor rather, at the attached house. The forge itself was cold, tools scattered where they'd been dropped. Lod was sitting at a table with a bottle, well past drunk and sliding toward unconscious.
"Kust's gone," he slurred when they asked about his apprentice. "Good boy. Gone."
"We know," Kyboah said. "We're trying to find him. Did he have any recent commissions? Anyone unusual he was working for?"
Lod waved vaguely at a shelf. "Ledger's there. Check the ledger. I can't... can't think about it."
They found the ledger and flipped through the recent entries. Near the end, they found what they were looking for:
Commission from Lord Valerius Caius. Custom silver fittings for the Hall of the Honored Dead. Pure silverΓÇövery specific request. Large order.
"Valerius," Saijah said. "Same name from the lumber order."
Just then, Nenya appeared in the doorway. They were beginning to suspect she had spies throughout the entire town.
"I have the key to the Wood Elf couple's home," she said without preamble. "The Salvians. Thought you might want to investigate there as well."
THE SALVIANS' HOME
The house was small but well-kept, the belongings of two people who'd lived long lives and traveled far. Everything was neat, organizedΓÇöexcept for the strange feeling that permeated the space.
Alfonso moved through the room with his hands outstretched, his eyes half-closed. "Magic was used here," he said. "Illusion school. Something designed to calm, to pacify." He frowned. "And Alteration. Advanced work. Allows the caster to become incorporealΓÇöpass through solid matter."
"That would explain the locked rooms," Kyboah said.
Saijah found a letter on a writing desk, addressed but never sent. She read it aloud:
"Dearest Marcus, We're closing our final deal here in Falkreath with Lord Valerius C. After this, we'll finally have enough to retire properly. We'll be home before the frost. Give our love to the grandchildren. Your mother and father."
"Valerius C," Saijah said. "That's three victims, all connected to someone named Valerius."
"Valerius Caius," Alfonso said, reading from the ledger they'd brought with them. "Lord Valerius Caius."
They looked at each other as the pieces came together.
"The door," Kyboah said. "It opens by speaking the caster's name."
"We have the name," Saijah confirmed.
"We have a deadline," Alfonso added. "The note said the ritual would be complete under the new moon. That's tomorrow night."
"Then we don't have much time," Kyboah said.
THE THRESHOLD
They returned to the Hall of the Honored Dead as the last light faded from the sky. The graveyard was utterly silent. Just the fog and the tombstones and the sealed door waiting before them.
The Nightshade blossom still sat on the threshold, darker now in the twilight.
Kyboah looked at the others. They nodded.
He turned to face the door and spoke clearly: "Valerius Caius."
Nothing happened.
They waited. Still nothing.
"Maybe it's the full name?" Saijah suggested. "Lord Valerius Caius?"
Alfonso shook his head. "No. Wards like this are keyed to the caster's true name, not titles." He paused, thinking. "The letter said 'Valerius C.' The ledger said 'Caius.' What if there's more to it?"
"Valerius Caelus," Ja'ha said suddenly. Everyone turned to look at her. She shrugged. "Old Imperial names. Caelus is more proper than Caius."
Alfonso considered this. "It's possible."
Kyboah turned back to the door. "Valerius Caelus."
The magical seal hissed and retracted, the ward dissolving like smoke.
The ancient stone door stood before them, no longer humming with magical energy. Just a door now. A door they could open.
Four people were inside. A ritual was scheduled for tomorrow night. And somewhere beyond that threshold was Lord Valerius CaelusΓÇöand whatever he was planning to do with his "collection."
The party stood in the fog-shrouded graveyard, the Nightshade blossom dark at their feet, the sealed Hall of the Honored Dead now unsealed and waiting.

